    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Sardinops ocellatus</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_3615",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Smallish, cylindrical fish with a single triangular dorsal fin that lacks spines, a forked tail and no lateral line. Mouth terminal with few to no teeth, but internally with up to 120 large gill rakers for filter feeding. Colour silvery blue with a distinctive row of 10–15 black spots along side.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3616",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 32 cm length but typically about 20 cm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3617",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread from Southern Africa across the Indo-Pacific, with distinct genetic lineages in Southern Africa, Australia, Chile, California and Japan.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Angola to southern Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3618",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Form huge pelagic schools and the target of a major purse seine fishery. The fishery landed up to 400 000 t in South Africa and 1.4 million t in Namibia at its peak in the 1960’s, but these catches were unsustainable and have since declined markedly. Also major source of food for numerous predatory species, including piscivorous fish such as snoek, tuna, yellowtail and kob, seabirds such as penguins and gannets, as well as sharks, dolphins and seals.</p><p>Undertakes complex migrations. Some spawn on the Agulhas Bank and their eggs drift westwards, juveniles congregating off the west coast in autumn and winter, then gradually working their way southwards back to the spawning grounds. Some also migrate inshore up the east coast in winter, following pockets of cooler water and resulting in the well-know sardine-run, in which dense schools are attacked by congregations of birds, fish, whales and dolphins, as well as by humans.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3619",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>The fish swim forward with the mouth widely gaping and gather microscopic phytoplankton, copepods and fish eggs on the enlarged gill rakers, which serve as an efficient filter-feeding apparatus.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3620",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Most of the stock spawns in spring and summer over the Agulhas Bank, with some also migrating to KZN where they spawn in winter and spring. The eggs and larvae are planktonic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3621",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Can be confused with various other small silvery schooling fish such as Redeye roundherring, but these lack the lateral spots and have the anal fin placed further back, behind the base of the dorsal fin. Anchovy are smaller (up to only 13 cm), lack the lateral spots, but have a silvery stripe along the flank and the snout projects forwards in front of the mouth.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3622",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 268).<br><br>Heemstra, P & Heemstra E (2004). Coastal Fishes of South Africa. NISC, Grahamstown. (p. 108).<br><br>Heemstra, P, Heemstra, E, Ebert, D, Holleman, W & Randall, J (2022). Coastal Fishes of the Western Indian Ocean. National Research Foundation & South African Institute for Aquatic Biodiversity, South Africa. Volume 2 (p. 151). <br><br>Smith, MM & Heemstra, P (eds.) (2003). Smith's Sea Fishes. Struik Publishers, Cape Town (p. 204 as <i>S. ocellatus</i>).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_3623",
